WEBVTT

0
00:00:06.389 --> 00:00:06.809
Hello,

1
00:00:07.389 --> 00:00:08.689
my name's Jen Webster,

2
00:00:08.750 --> 00:00:12.189
and I'm a chartered psychologist here at the Health and Safety Laboratory.

3
00:00:12.560 --> 00:00:15.689
And part of my job is to help organizations understand

4
00:00:15.920 --> 00:00:18.930
and improve their safety culture using our ascent model.

5
00:00:19.430 --> 00:00:23.049
And one of the questions I'm frequently asked is what is safety culture?

6
00:00:23.469 --> 00:00:26.260
So I thought I'd give you a brief explanation about what it is,

7
00:00:26.549 --> 00:00:27.450
why it's important,

8
00:00:27.909 --> 00:00:29.989
and how you can measure your safety culture.

9
00:00:36.799 --> 00:00:39.639
The term safety culture was first used in an

10
00:00:39.639 --> 00:00:43.599
initial report published by the International Atomic Energy Agency

11
00:00:43.840 --> 00:00:45.689
way back in 1986,

12
00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:49.580
which identified the organizational and managerial failures

13
00:00:49.680 --> 00:00:51.849
that contributed to the Chernobyl disaster.

14
00:00:52.529 --> 00:00:54.290
And in 1993,

15
00:00:54.369 --> 00:00:58.229
HSE's Advisory Committee on the Safety of Nuclear installations

16
00:00:58.610 --> 00:01:00.790
produced their definition of safety culture.

17
00:01:01.169 --> 00:01:04.050
They said that safety culture of an organization

18
00:01:04.279 --> 00:01:07.449
is the product of individual and group values,

19
00:01:07.569 --> 00:01:08.330
attitudes,

20
00:01:08.449 --> 00:01:09.209
perceptions,

21
00:01:09.330 --> 00:01:10.209
competencies,

22
00:01:10.449 --> 00:01:11.900
and patterns of behavior

23
00:01:12.089 --> 00:01:13.839
that determine the commitment to,

24
00:01:14.089 --> 00:01:15.830
and the style and proficiency

25
00:01:16.010 --> 00:01:18.470
of an organisation's health and safety management.

26
00:01:19.989 --> 00:01:23.650
Some have described safety culture as an organisation's personality.

27
00:01:24.029 --> 00:01:27.830
Another way of thinking about safety culture is the way things are done around here.

28
00:01:34.419 --> 00:01:34.819
Now,

29
00:01:34.940 --> 00:01:37.419
often you'll see alongside safety culture,

30
00:01:37.580 --> 00:01:40.239
the term safety climate also being used,

31
00:01:40.660 --> 00:01:43.540
and it's not unusual for them to be used interchangeably,

32
00:01:43.739 --> 00:01:45.089
even by the experts.

33
00:01:45.919 --> 00:01:48.580
And to illustrate the differences between the two,

34
00:01:49.160 --> 00:01:51.339
I'd like to use the iceberg metaphor,

35
00:01:51.629 --> 00:01:51.739
you know,

36
00:01:51.769 --> 00:01:53.879
what you see and what you don't see.

37
00:01:54.900 --> 00:01:57.699
Safety climate relates to the perceptions held across

38
00:01:57.699 --> 00:02:00.489
the workforce at a given moment in time

39
00:02:00.860 --> 00:02:02.959
about the way things are done around here.

40
00:02:03.300 --> 00:02:04.139
It's measurable.

41
00:02:05.129 --> 00:02:07.860
Safety culture is the underlying shared values,

42
00:02:08.008 --> 00:02:08.360
beliefs,

43
00:02:08.369 --> 00:02:12.289
and habitual working practices that influence health and safety performance,

44
00:02:12.529 --> 00:02:14.389
and these are not always apparent.

45
00:02:14.809 --> 00:02:15.600
In other words,

46
00:02:15.809 --> 00:02:16.889
like this iceberg,

47
00:02:17.089 --> 00:02:20.910
the scale and extent of any issues relating to your safety culture

48
00:02:21.220 --> 00:02:22.990
may not be in your line of sight.

49
00:02:29.440 --> 00:02:31.779
So why should you measure safety climate?

50
00:02:32.240 --> 00:02:32.360
Well,

51
00:02:32.440 --> 00:02:35.389
looking back at 30 years of safety climate research,

52
00:02:35.740 --> 00:02:38.720
Dv Zohar described safety climate as a robust

53
00:02:38.720 --> 00:02:41.740
leading indicator of health and safety performance.

54
00:02:42.240 --> 00:02:46.279
And we know that organizations with a successful health and safety record

55
00:02:46.559 --> 00:02:50.470
use an appropriate mix of both leading and lagging indicators.

56
00:02:51.979 --> 00:02:53.729
As you can see on the left hand side,

57
00:02:54.270 --> 00:02:57.210
safety climate consists of a number of antecedents.

58
00:02:58.639 --> 00:03:02.179
These are the elements that contribute towards a strong safety culture.

59
00:03:03.369 --> 00:03:06.389
By understanding the safety climate in your organization,

60
00:03:06.770 --> 00:03:08.410
you can build on your strengths,

61
00:03:08.809 --> 00:03:10.750
focus on areas for improvement,

62
00:03:11.050 --> 00:03:11.889
and in doing so,

63
00:03:12.050 --> 00:03:13.149
you will find you have

64
00:03:13.250 --> 00:03:15.089
less injuries and near misses

65
00:03:15.330 --> 00:03:17.399
and a workforce that is both competent,

66
00:03:17.690 --> 00:03:20.029
motivated and engaged to work safely.

67
00:03:21.610 --> 00:03:25.089
So I've explained what safety culture is and why you should measure it.

68
00:03:25.839 --> 00:03:27.199
But where should you start?

69
00:03:28.800 --> 00:03:30.419
It's important to have a plan,

70
00:03:30.759 --> 00:03:33.380
and we recommend you use HSL's ascent model

71
00:03:33.679 --> 00:03:34.500
to guide you

72
00:03:34.839 --> 00:03:36.619
through the change that you want to make,

73
00:03:37.240 --> 00:03:39.789
and you do this through a series of manageable steps.

74
00:03:40.770 --> 00:03:41.330
First,

75
00:03:41.580 --> 00:03:44.229
build your foundation for what you want to achieve

76
00:03:44.539 --> 00:03:47.710
and get the support of key stakeholders in your organization.

77
00:03:48.699 --> 00:03:52.710
Analyze your current safety culture by using HSL's safety climate tool

78
00:03:52.869 --> 00:03:56.130
to give you a baseline that will act as your anchor moving forward.

79
00:03:56.899 --> 00:03:58.339
Focus on your results,

80
00:03:58.660 --> 00:04:01.259
use the survey data to engage and involve the

81
00:04:01.259 --> 00:04:03.919
workforce in decisions about what needs to change,

82
00:04:04.619 --> 00:04:06.139
and then form an action plan.

83
00:04:06.380 --> 00:04:07.460
If you follow the model,

84
00:04:07.500 --> 00:04:11.100
you'll be able to make evidence based decisions to develop your action plan.

85
00:04:12.130 --> 00:04:13.050
And finally,

86
00:04:13.300 --> 00:04:15.250
you should evaluate how you're doing

87
00:04:15.449 --> 00:04:19.390
as it's important to keep the momentum going as part of your overall plan

88
00:04:19.529 --> 00:04:21.108
for continuous improvement.

89
00:04:21.820 --> 00:04:24.600
If you'd like to find out more about safety culture

90
00:04:24.980 --> 00:04:26.559
or HSL's ascent model.

91
00:04:27.670 --> 00:04:30.149
Join us on one of our first steps webinars

92
00:04:30.510 --> 00:04:37.790
and ask for our free white papers by contacting product support at HSL.gSI.gov.uk.